node.text:
Woooo I got the chance to interview the Head of Instagram @mosseri ! I added some timestamps if you have a short attention span like me and you want to skip around. My favorite question is at 9 minutes btw

My biggest takeaways:

🏆 How do I get verified?
He actually answered my question and wasn't just vague about it! The answer is press. They look for press about you from reputable publications. 

📉 Why is my engagement down?
It's not because the algorithm hates you. It's getting more and more competitive every day on not just IG but on all social media platforms as more and more creators are making content.

🌏 Why is Reels not yet available yet in my country?
Turns out it's a music licensing issue, which they're working on before they can roll out Reels to everyone

🤭 What does @mosseri think TikTok does better than IG
Wooo so glad I got to ask this one and he actually delivered a real answer, no BS
Skip to 9:00 for his answer

--
Btw, here's what I think about Instagram vs TikTok -

TikTok is better at finding the niche for your content. Their algorithm is very good at finding the audience for specific interests - whether it be filmmaking, reality TV gossip, tie dye techniques, anything. The Reels algorithm to me doesn't seem as advanced. It rewards generic content, like general dance or comedy videos that have mass appeal. This makes it harder for niche creators to blow up on Reels.

TikTok is an absolute roller coaster. It operates on a hit or flop system. A small percentage of your videos will go massively viral, but most of them just kinda flop. That is really rough on creator psychology. For a long time I dreaded posting on TikTok for this reason, it was incredibly discouraging.

While TikTok is much better at getting you more followers, those followers are worth nowhere near as much as an IG follower or a YouTube subscriber. That's by design btw - TikTok's algorithm prioritizes showing you people you don't follow, rather than people you do follow. 

But the biggest consideration - is $$$. Which platform pays better -

node.text:
I never went to film school. There’s so many gaps in my filmmaking knowledge, and there’s been so many times when I’m trying to get the shot, where I’m thinking - I have no idea what I’m doing
﻿
﻿But because there’s so much I don’t know, often times that forces me to find simpler, easier solutions for shots. Like how we got my hair to float up for my most recent campaign for the LG gram laptop :)
﻿
﻿I’d always wanted a big screen to be able to edit on the go, but never got one before cause I’m a tiny person who doesn’t like wearing heavy backpacks. I edited this shot on the LG gram laptop and was floored by how powerful the machine is despite being so light. And the SCREEN! 17 inches 😍 It was so much nicer to be able to edit on a big screen
﻿@lgusa #LGPartner
﻿
﻿@_beckybhanot left an insightful comment on my last video that she’s “adding careers”﻿, not “changing careers”. I absolutely love this mindset - because you still keep all the skills you learned in your previous careers.
﻿
﻿#motivation #inspiration #careergoals #careerdevelopment #careeradvice #LGgram
﻿

node.text:
I’ve changed careers 4 times now. Every time I do it I think… again, really?? It’s daunting to feel like you’re starting all over and you’re behind everyone else who’s been in that career for longer.
﻿
﻿What’s helped me get through all these career changes was a lesson I learned when I was a kid. Kinda random, but it was when I learned how to spin a book on my finger. A “useless” skill I learned that became useful when I used it for a marketing campaign for the LG gram laptop @lgusa #LGPartner
﻿
﻿Also please excuse my link-baity title for this video. The career I was in before filmmaking was marketing, so you can blame that ;)
﻿
﻿#motivation #inspiration #careergoals #careerdevelopment #careeradvice #LGgram
﻿

Trip ideas by @karenxcheng - I am not responsible for any stolen luggage 😅

Decided to make a tutorial for some of the travel shots I've done over the years 

Editing tutorial here: karenx.com/travelshots (link in bio)

1. Airport Dolly Zoom
I'm obsessed with dolly zooms, they're one of my favorite effects. I was coming back from SFO when I saw the airport walkway and got the idea to use it for this effect. Make sure you're being mindful of your fellow travelers and only attempt this when no one else is near the walkway!

2. Running Train Shot
I first saw this effect in a 5mincraft video from 2019. If you know the original creator who came up with this, please leave a comment & let me know so I can credit them. I made some edits to sell the motion in this effect:  added a speed ramp, digital camera shake, and motion blur in Premiere / After Effects

3.  Everyone is walking backwards
Have you seen Spike Jonze's iconic music video to Pharcyde's "Drop"? He made an entire music video to this reverse effect in 1995. That's over 25 years ago 🤯  So completely ahead of his time.  This is my modern take on it with an iPhone and a selfie stick 🤳 I noticed that the hardest part of a classic reverse walk is to get the walking motion to look convincing, but if you use a selfie stick it can hide the imperfections in your walking technique. 

4. Souvenir landmark transition
A few years ago I visited Paris and I was trying to think of an idea for the Eiffel Tower. When I was walking around I saw the souvenirs being sold everywhere and I got the idea to do a match cut and it worked! Recently I was in Seattle and wanted to make a tutorial for the effect, this time with the Space Needle. But I much prefer the original Eiffel Tower shot :)

How we made the @logitech spot! Collab with @tommylundberg We moved the mouse 1 inch at a time, while also moving the tripod 1 inch at a time. Afterwards, Tommy manually lined up all the images one at a time in Photoshop to get a more stabilized look.

Client: @logitech #ad #WorkLifeUpgraded
Director: @karenxcheng
DP & Editor: @tommylundberg

As part of this campaign, #Logitech hooked me up with their mouse, keyboard, and webcam 

Here’s my review after using it for the last few months:
tbh I never thought that much about my mouse and keyboard setup before this. Which is kinda silly because I’m a very tactile person. I obsess about how things feel - little things like wooden spoons and bowls and the right smush-factor on my pillows.

I spend 8 hours a day on my mouse and keyboard, which is like half my waking hours on this thing! So it’s actually really important that they feel nice.

The keyboard - It just feels good to press down on the keys. They have the right bounce to them. Each key is shaped with a little dip that my finger fits nicely into. The mouse wheel - I’m obsessed with the mouse wheel. It has a very satisfying scroll. I never realized before that scrolling could be so satisfying?? It’s very precise which helps me when I’m doing precise editing work. 

The webcam - I dunno what witchcraft they are working on their webcam, but it is doing something with the lighting and it’s very flattering. I’m too lazy to wear makeup most of the time (I put it on for videos and that’s it, I can’t be bothered to put on makeup for a zoom call) so this webcam is perfect.

Mouse - MX Anywhere 3 #MXAnywhere3
Keyboard - MX Keys
Webcam - Logitech BRIO

I've discovered the ultimate camera accessory 🙋🏻‍♀️ Shoutout to everyone who guessed, so many creative ones! The fastest Swiffer guessers are tagged in my stories and comments 🧹

Made this for @adobecreate - I've got a tutorial and editing breakdown at the bottom of this page: karenx.com/lowbudget 

🧹 Level 1: Basic Camera Sweep
So I started playing around with the idea of using a Swiffer last year when quarantine first started. I did this shot back then and was really pleased with how useful the swivel head on this thing was to get smooth shots. If you've been following me for a while you might remember this one, which I first posted about a year ago!

🧹 Level 2: Extra Long Swiffer
Then I realized that because Swiffer are modular, you can chain several of them together to make an extra-long "drone" pole. A lot cheaper than the professional drone poles on the market which can set you back a few hundred bucks! Back in March I tried this with a painter's pole, but now having tried both methods I far prefer the Swiffer pole - it's way more light and portable.

🧹 Level 3: Swiffering with Friends
Originally I attempted to do this with just two Swiffers (using my Level 1 rig but adding another Swiffer jutting out perpendicular to it). But this ended up not working because the rig wasn't stable and the shot kept going crooked. So we added a 3rd Swiffer to the other side to stabilize and that ended up working really well!

Low budget Superman 🦸🏻‍♂️ BTS of my shoot for Philips Espresso 👇 See below for how to remove the mattress 

I wanted to do this jump shot, but I definitely don't have the athletic ability that those parkour guys do. So I decided to put a mattress on the ground for me to fall down on so I could have better form and not worry about landing on my face. We pushed the mattress bit by bit on the ground to create a fun stop motion effect.

Trying to get a consistent jump was tricky. My jumps were all over the place at first and had inconsistent body position / height, so we had to start over a few times. But after several dozen attempts, I finally got my jumping technique down. 

How to remove the mattress:
👉 Keep your camera or phone on a tripod the whole time
👉 Make sure to get a picture of the room WITHOUT the mattress. Shoot this using the exact same settings you shot your jumps
👉 In the edit, create a top/bottom split screen. On the bottom half, use the part of the room without the mattress. Many editing apps support this, we used @adobevideo Premiere Pro
👉 Tip: use an air mattress, it's much easier to push along on the floor

Just another day in the office 🤷🏻‍♀️ On our shoot for Philips Espresso @philipshomelivingna ☕️ I'll share BTS for the flying scene tomorrow!

For this slide-along-the-ground stop motion, originally the plan was for me to get up in between shots and move myself. But then my clothes started wrinkling too much in between shots, which made the stop motion effect less smooth. So instead we came up with the plan for @justinoliphant to push me forward, so I could stay as still as possible in between shots. 

Also check my stories highlight "coffee" for the interactive version of this. I first had this idea 5 years ago, remember when planking was a meme?? I made this just for fun back then with @vonwong. When I need to pitch concepts to clients, I will often look back at my personal projects to see if any of the ideas could fit for a client. And dusted this one off from five years ago and got paid for it this time 🙌

Swipe for the reveal ➡️ New work for ☕️ Philips Espresso! @philipshomelivingna Can you tell how we shot the flying scene? (Swipe to see it) I'll share behind-the-scenes this week!

🤔 Hint 1: I am *not* particularly athletic
🕵🏻‍♀️ Hint 2: watch the hair

#ad ☕️ We also made an interactive IG stories (tap on my “coffee” highlight) where you can tap around and “make me a coffee”. Coffee fuels so much creative work, so I was excited to try this machine after reading the rave reviews about it. I really appreciate that it grinds the beans for me inside the machine and that there's no milk cleanup (no tubes!!)

It’s a button press and then I can relax and take a moment of pause while it makes my coffee for me. Btw I only recently started learning how important it is to relax. Before I literally didn’t understand what "relaxing" meant. People would talk about relaxing, but I physically did not know how to relax myself, so it was just an abstract concept for me, like differential equations or quantum physics 🤷🏻‍♀️🤔

Growing up in an immigrant household, I was trained to believe I needed to be productive every waking second, otherwise I was LAZY. It took me a long time to get out of this mindset, but over time I’ve realized that I actually come up with my best ideas when I’m relaxed or bored - not when I’m trying to force myself to be productive all the time.

Woooo I got the chance to interview the Head of Instagram @mosseri ! I added some timestamps if you have a short attention span like me and you want to skip around. My favorite question is at 9 minutes btw

My biggest takeaways:

🏆 How do I get verified?
He actually answered my question and wasn't just vague about it! The answer is press. They look for press about you from reputable publications. 

📉 Why is my engagement down?
It's not because the algorithm hates you. It's getting more and more competitive every day on not just IG but on all social media platforms as more and more creators are making content.

🌏 Why is Reels not yet available yet in my country?
Turns out it's a music licensing issue, which they're working on before they can roll out Reels to everyone

🤭 What does @mosseri think TikTok does better than IG
Wooo so glad I got to ask this one and he actually delivered a real answer, no BS
Skip to 9:00 for his answer

--
Btw, here's what I think about Instagram vs TikTok -

TikTok is better at finding the niche for your content. Their algorithm is very good at finding the audience for specific interests - whether it be filmmaking, reality TV gossip, tie dye techniques, anything. The Reels algorithm to me doesn't seem as advanced. It rewards generic content, like general dance or comedy videos that have mass appeal. This makes it harder for niche creators to blow up on Reels.

TikTok is an absolute roller coaster. It operates on a hit or flop system. A small percentage of your videos will go massively viral, but most of them just kinda flop. That is really rough on creator psychology. For a long time I dreaded posting on TikTok for this reason, it was incredibly discouraging.

While TikTok is much better at getting you more followers, those followers are worth nowhere near as much as an IG follower or a YouTube subscriber. That's by design btw - TikTok's algorithm prioritizes showing you people you don't follow, rather than people you do follow. 

But the biggest consideration - is $$$. Which platform pays better -

Kick shot idea with @winnieharlow for @puma ! This is the 2nd shot I did with her - we had just 10 minutes to get both shots, which was very nerve wracking for me. 

She had a full day shoot with a large crew getting hundreds of campaign photos, and in the middle of that she squeezed in 10 minutes with me to get these shots for Puma's TikTok.

While she was doing other parts of her photoshoot, I prepped everything I could without her - I was lucky enough to have another stand-in model to work with in order to test all the variables: the choreography, lighting, location, angles. That way I could make sure everything was buttoned up on my side when @winnieharlow was ready for me, so I could have her in and out as fast as possible. She nailed both shots on her first attempt 💪💪

Shot & edited by @karenxcheng
Client: @puma
Featuring @winnieharlow
BTS @laurencuddy
